##Deep Breath in an outbreak. We got ta get out of here

Micro Signal Xiezuozheyunshegong

FUNCTION INTRODUCTION: Volunteer Information Management, social worker information management, public welfare information release, social work professional exchange

This article is one of the case interviews carried out by the collaborators in the "Peasant Workers' anti-epidemic Rescue Action" , aiming at quickly identifying the vulnerable groups in the epidemic situation and their needs, and providing reference for the epidemic prevention, control and rescue work, we've put together a list to share with you.
Deep breathing in case of an outbreak
A case study of the migrant workers'families in difficulty in Foshan (15)

This outbreak, it needs to be over

Narrator: Koume (not his real name) from Xinyang, Henan Province
Place of employment: Beijing

Editor's Note: Koume, female, 44 years old, graduated from a technical secondary school, Henan migrant worker in Beijing, suffering from hypertension, diabetes. Husband does exterior wall cleaning, also do part-time worker, suffer from Lumbar intervertebral disc protrusion. Koume, a substitute teacher at a private school for children of migrant workers, earns about 2,000 yuan a month after taking out five insurance policies. Her husband earns 4,000 yuan a month, and the family of six barely makes ends meet.

Had to stay in Beijing for the New Year because of the epidemic

We had planned to return home on December twenty-eight. The father had a cleaning job he wanted to do but couldn't because of the epidemic. December twenty-seven, 8 to hear about this illness, began not to attach importance to the new year's Day suddenly network, wechat everywhere on this, just feel serious.

I used to go home every year. My grandmother was in her 80s. I went home every year. There's no going back this time, and the father has no choice but to wait until the epidemic is over and find time to go back. Now this situation family members do not let us go back, go back also had to be isolated, had to stay in Beijing, the road for fear of Greater Risk, Henan is also a major disaster area, than here are serious.

We have two courtyards here, hundreds of working families from all over the country, from the 12th month twenty-one to the 12th month twenty-seven, the 12th month of the 12th month of the 12th month of the 12th month of the 12th month of the 12th month of the 12th month of the 12th month of the 12th month of the 12th month of the 12th month of the 12th month, have been It's safer for us. Now there is no one to give us any publicity to what protective measures, all are watching the news, know that the situation is serious, do not let the children out, in fact, there is no place to go.

Now, our side of the community is also sealed off, there is a community team on duty, set up checkpoints, the courtyard of other people have also come back, have also informed the need to quarantine at home, we do not go out. One at a time on our side, all sealed and not allowed to go anywhere. That's not the problem. The problem is that you can't go out and buy anything without money.

The hallway in front of Koume's house (August 2019)
If you feel uncomfortable, consult your co-worker

I have high blood pressure, diabetes, weak body fat, but also often take medicine. The father has a herniated disc and can't do heavy work at work, so some of the work can't be done. Usually do not go to the hospital, usually also catch a cold and have a fever, go to the village clinic to get some medicine on the line.

We don't have a contract, I have five policies, his dad has nothing, and he's not even steady at work. At least I have insurance. It would be better if I saw a doctor in Beijing, but I wouldn't go if I was fine. Both the father and the child are the new farmers'cooperative in the family, nothing else. One is do not know what insurance, also can not afford, can live on the good, did not think of the insurance of things. His father worked as a temporary worker, and he usually worked wherever there was work to be done. The boss would not consider providing insurance, nor did he himself. In order to have insurance, they all had to be insured continuously. The families we work for rarely have the means to do so, i don't think more than 90% of working families do.

Social workers light candles with children during a visit to the Koume family during a power outage in November 2017

In terms of protection, we know to wear a mask, pay attention to disinfection. We have the original school issued anti-smog Masks, I kept some, I do not know if it fits the situation. The door elder sister is a cleaning, their leader gave her half bottle of 84 disinfectant, she came back to see me did not, and poured me a little, told me dilution can disinfection. Now there is no child's mask at home, there is no children's special, I let them stay at home as much as possible. The boss can use an adult's mask, but not two small ones. I don't think it's secure. I told them there was a virus out there, and they didn't get out much. I know the basic symptoms of a new pneumonia, but I don't know which hospital to go to. If you feel sick, consult your co-worker.
I know more than I did in 2003 when I was in SARS

This courtyard is basically the field, after the New Year do not know when to come back, back do not know if there are special measures, now is not felt. When people are back, may be more dangerous, people, dense, then even more dare not let the child to run back and forth. But you can't keep someone from coming back.

KOUME's family built a community self-help library where children can read and borrow books (photo taken in August 2019) 

Compared to SARS in 2003, we know more information than before. We used to guess. It's all over the phone now. Friends Circle, wechat group home what can know, I have seen where we dig a road to set up roadblocks to the village closed. Now we all know what's going on. Now I can't get out of the house, which means I check my phone every day, nothing else.

This outbreak should be over soon. What happened to 15 days of Home Quarantine? These days aren't over yet, and we know the impact is too great.
The biggest worry, of course, is work. If you can't work, you can't afford it

It's not convenient to buy vegetables in the early period of our life. My family is buying cabbage, potatoes and some green vegetables just before the Spring Festival. I rarely buy food online. Besides, I can't buy food online.

Now better, can buy some things, we now mainly eat vegetables, small rape more than two yuan a catty, potatoes two yuan a catty, spinach more than three yuan a catty. We all buy the cheapest vegetables, fortunately here from the vegetable wholesale market a little closer, vegetables than other places have been a lot cheaper. But the frame can not bear several children to eat, each time is doing, eating, food is done, they are almost finished. Several children wake up every morning saying that they are hungry and want to eat. The children can eat rice on the good, not picky, I go to the supermarket to buy three or four bags of noodles, come back their steamed bread, noodles.

The old man in the family was watched by his father, brother and aunt. We called the old man every day. At first I thought it would only be half a month, if it lasted for two months, we would surely have no way to live, now I only have minimum wage, the father of the child would certainly not be able to go out to work with an epidemic, the family of six must eat, i still have to pay the living expenses and rent for the old people in my hometown, which all have to be paid for. Besides, a few children go to school, and now they watch TV at home every day and do homework for a long time. Is that a problem? This outbreak, it needs to be over.

The walls of the house were plastered with awards from the children

The biggest worry, of course, is work. It's always been this way. Without work, there's no money. These days better, the courtyard of the landlord let the child's father to help to look at the door to do registration and so on, give a little fee, the landlord is to see us no income is very difficult. In addition to life and children's learning, the eldest son here in the home school, school notice extension, do not know when to start school; three small is waiting for notice. The eldest son Sophomore, choose science, physics, mathematics is not good, I can not tutor, now the course is not up to, there is no good way. I could use a little help with the three little ones, so far.

We're using two credit cards upside down, and yesterday I paid off the $8,000 on my card to the father. No choice but to do so, now relatives and friends have no money, no place to borrow, they are also inverted credit cards or borrowed money. We know this isn't the way, but if there's a mistake, don't make any mistakes, compromise your credit, and don't fine me again.

For the future, we have to wait. We can't work until the epidemic is over. I hope it's over soon. I hope I get a job. I don't have any other plans.

Social Worker's notes

Koume, a substitute teacher at a migrant children's school who has experienced SARS, was not too nervous about the outbreak. She is worried about the life of her family, four children between the ages of 9 and 17, who have to go to school in addition to food. If the epidemic continues, the family's living expenses, rent, water and electricity will not be sustained on her basic salary alone, and now they need to borrow to make ends meet. But KOUME is hopeful that the outbreak will soon be over and that business as usual will continue.
Service advice
Now:
1. Coordinate with Angel Volunteers to help your boss with his homework if he needs to go home to study
2. Through an online service, accompanying angels and Social Workers Provide "peer support groups" for their eldest son to provide emotional and learning support;
3. Provide online services such as tutoring, interest classes, and angels for other children
4, continue to follow up on the family situation, to understand the next step of family life planning, to help during the epidemic period of normal life.

LONG-TERM:
1. Provide Employment Information and advice to the father of the child to prepare him for work after the outbreak and ease the family's financial difficulties;
2. Coordinate resources to enable them to participate in health check-up services to monitor their physical health;
3. After the end of the epidemic, to continue to provide school assistance to the family, including assistance for small amounts of school funds to ease the pressure on children's school fees.
